<ArticleLayout
  title="Bedroom Drawers That Open Without Crowding the Room"
  description="Choose a tallboy or dresser for the clothes that need folding and the floor space its drawers occupy when fully open."
  category="Bedroom"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="10 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/bedroom.webp"
  imageAlt="A calm bedroom with a timber dresser, folded clothes and warm natural light"
>
  <p>
    A tallboy is often bought to solve the clean-clothes basket and creates a second problem when its
    drawers open into the walkway or its top becomes another permanent pile.
  </p>
  <p>
    Sort the clothes first. Identify what genuinely folds, what hangs and what can leave the room.
    Then mark the furniture footprint, full drawer extension and the standing space needed to use it.
    Capacity only helps when the unit fits the room and can be used safely.
  </p>

  <h2>Define What the Drawers Will Hold</h2>
  <p>
    Underwear, socks, sleepwear, activewear, T-shirts and folded uniforms suit drawers when each
    category has enough room to return after washing. Paperwork, old electronics, shopping bags and
    unrelated household overflow do not justify another piece of bedroom furniture.
  </p>
  <p>
    Decide what should hang, move under the bed or leave the household. The{" "}
    <a href="/guides/bedroom-wardrobe-organisation-what-to-sort-before-buying-storage/">wardrobe organisation guide</a>{" "}
    covers hanging and folding decisions; the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/under-bed-storage-what-to-measure-before-you-buy/">under-bed storage guide</a>{" "}
    suits seasonal and occasional items.
  </p>

  <h2>Choose Height or Width for a Reason</h2>
  <p>
    A tallboy uses less wall width and makes upper drawers harder for some people to reach. A low
    dresser needs more floor and wall space but can offer wide, accessible drawers. Its generous top
    can also attract folded laundry, skincare and devices.
  </p>
  <p>
    Match drawer proportions to the clothes. Shallow drawers keep small items visible; deep drawers
    suit bulky jumpers and can bury socks. Wide drawers grow heavy when full. Count the categories and
    test folded items in a box of similar dimensions before choosing the shape.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure the Unit With Every Drawer Open</h2>
  <p>
    Record wall width and furniture depth, then add the full drawer extension and standing space.
    Check the bed, wardrobe tracks, bedroom and ensuite doors, balcony access, rugs and the main route
    through the room. Open nearby furniture while the outline is marked on the floor.
  </p>
  <p>
    Also note windows, curtain drops, power points, vents and skirting. If the same wall is involved
    in a lighting or curtain change, see the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/bedroom-lighting-and-window-coverings-what-to-compare-before-you-buy/">bedroom lighting and window coverings guide</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Inspect Drawers, Runners and Handles</h2>
  <p>
    Pull every drawer out and close it several times. Check whether it remains aligned, stops as
    intended and can be removed only as described in the instructions. A smooth empty drawer may feel
    very different once loaded.
  </p>
  <p>
    Compare the maker's load limits with the intended contents. Protruding handles can catch clothing
    in a narrow path, while recessed pulls may be harder for some hands. Soft-close runners are a
    convenience; reliable travel, secure stops and suitable construction matter more.
  </p>

  <h2>Take Toppling Risk Seriously</h2>
  <p>
    Opening drawers shifts weight forward, and a child can use them as steps. Since 4 May 2025,
    covered furniture supplied in Australia—including clothing-storage units at least 686 mm high—
    has been subject to a mandatory information standard for toppling warnings.
  </p>
  <p>
    Look for the required warnings, anchoring information and stable construction. The{" "}
    <a href="https://www.productsafety.gov.au/consumers/be-safe-around-the-home/use-products-inside-the-home-safely/toppling-furniture-and-televisions-guide" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ACCC toppling-furniture guide</a>{" "}
    recommends anchoring furniture, keeping heavy items low and not placing items that attract
    children on top. Use the supplied instructions and anchoring method suitable for the product and
    wall or floor. A renter should speak with the landlord or agent rather than leaving furniture
    unsecured because approval is needed.
  </p>

  <h2>Plan the Top Surface Before It Arrives</h2>
  <p>
    Decide whether the dresser top will hold a small tray, lamp or nothing at all. Heavy objects and
    televisions do not belong on furniture that is not designed and secured for them. Keep the
    surface clear enough to open curtains, clean and put clothes away.
  </p>
  <p>
    If glasses, charging and water are migrating to the dresser, the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/bedside-table-setup-what-to-check-before-you-buy/">bedside table guide</a>{" "}
    may solve that routine with less floor space.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep Clothing Categories Simple</h2>
  <p>
    Give daily workwear, uniforms and activewear the easiest drawers. Seasonal pieces can move to a
    less convenient zone. Dividers help only after each drawer has a job; too many compartments make
    the system slower to reset.
  </p>
  <p>
    Spare linen belongs here only when it serves this bedroom and remains in complete sets. The{" "}
    <a href="/guides/bedding-and-linen-basics-for-australian-bedrooms/">bedding and linen guide</a>{" "}
    helps decide what to keep and where to store it.
  </p>

  <h2>Allow for Flooring, Cleaning and Change</h2>
  <p>
    A unit must sit level and stable on the actual floor. Carpet can be thicker near a wall; rugs and
    uneven transitions can affect stability and drawer movement. Follow the manufacturer's levelling
    and placement directions rather than packing beneath a leg improvised materials.
  </p>
  <p>
    Check whether dust can be removed from beneath and whether the unit can remain secured if the room
    changes. Guest rooms benefit from an empty drawer more than furniture full of household overflow.
    Shared rooms need assigned categories, not necessarily matching halves.
  </p>

  <h2>Check the Whole Unit Before Buying</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Sort the clothes and list the drawer categories.</li>
    <li>Mark the closed footprint, full drawer extension and standing space.</li>
    <li>Check doors, robe tracks, windows, vents and walkways.</li>
    <li>Inspect drawer stops, runners, handles and stated load limits.</li>
    <li>Look for required toppling warnings and plan suitable anchoring.</li>
    <li>Keep heavy contents low and prevent the top becoming overflow.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The strongest choice is not the unit with the most drawers. It is the one that opens fully,
    stores the folded clothes that remain after sorting and leaves the room safe to move through.
    Browse the{" "}
    <a href="/categories/bedroom/">Bedroom</a>{" "}
    category and our{" "}
    <a href="/guides/bedroom-storage-ideas-small-australian-rooms/">small bedroom storage guide</a>{" "}
    for the rest of the room.
  </p>

